[normal]CONCLUSION[bold]2
[normal]8
[normal].  The proposals in respect of
[normal] civil legal aid 
[normal]funding are of genuine 
[normal]constitutional importance and should be rejected on constitutional
[normal], human rights and democratic
[normal] grounds.
[normal]2
[normal]9
[normal].  
[normal]No executive body
[normal] likes to have its decisions overturned in court (any more than it likes them to be criticised in the press).   But no citizen wa
[normal]nts to live in a country where the government regards itself as 
[normal]ab
[normal]ove and unconstrained by 
[normal]law.  A
[normal] credible and effective  judicial mechanism for ensuring that the executive acts within its lawful authority is essential to the rule of law.  As Lord Pannick
[normal] QC 
[normal]has recently remarked
[normal],
[normal] 
[normal] those countries in which the Government win
[normal]s
[normal] all 
[normal]its
[normal] cases in court are not places in which any of us would wish to live
[normal].
